Taint Effect:
=============
Syntax

# kubectl taint nodes node1 key1=value1:NoSchedule
# kubectl taint nodes node1 key1=value1:NoExecute
# kubectl taint nodes node1 key2=value1:PreferNoSchedule

# kubectl taint node kube-node1 size=large:NoSchedule

conditions
==========
1. Not mention operator.

  tolerations:
      - key: size
        value: large
        effect: NoSchedule

      => if you not mention operator in tolerations, then it will automatically take Equal operator which is bydefault.

2. If the value not match

  tolerations:
      - key: size
        operator: Equal
        value: abc
        effect: NoSchedule

     => then the pod will stuck in pending state.

3. allow all taint to tolerance all pods.

  tolerations:
      - key: ""
        operator: Exist
        effect: ""
==========================================================


Example-1 (Equal)

kubectl taint nodes k3d-worker-node-0 taint=start:NoSchedule

  tolerations:
      - key: taint
        operator: Equal
        value: start
        effect: NoSchedule

Example-2 (Exists)

  tolerations:
      - key: size
        operator: Exists
        effect: NoSchedule

  ==> In that case it will work according to key should present on node. value does not need to mention.


are 3 types:

Hard effect:-
=============
1) NoSchedule: it does not evict(delete) existing pod from Node even they don't have tolerance.
                => But if you delete/migrate existing pod then it will not run again on taint node without tolerance.

2) NoExcure: It basically terminate all existing pod from node if they don't have tolerations repective this nodes.


Soft effect:-
=============
3) PreferNoSchedule:  A soft effect where the system will try to avoid placing a pod that does not tolerate the taint on the node unless necessary.
                      (rarelly use on servers)


